nineteen months of ethnographic work with five congregations to better understand why group Bible study matters so much to Evangelicals and for Evangelical culture. Through a close analysis of participants' discourse, Bielo examines the defining themes of group life-from textual interpretation to spiritual intimacy and the rehearsal of witnessing. Bielo's approach allows these Evangelical groups to speak for themselves, illustrating Bible study's uniqueness in Evangelical life as a site of open and critical dialogue. Ultimately, Bielo's ethnography sheds much needed light on the power of group Bible study for the ever-evolving shape of American Evangelicalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aChristian sociologyxProtestant churches. 0aChurch group workxProtestant churches. 0aEvangelicalismzMichiganzLansing Region. 0aEvangelicalismzMichiganzLansing. 0aSmall groupsxReligious aspectsxProtestant churches. 7aBIBLES / God's Word / Study.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aBible.  aBielos.  aEvangelicalism.  aethnography.  aever-evolving.  agroup.  alight.  amuch.  aneeded.  apower.  ashape.  asheds.  astudy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081479121940uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814789995.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814789995423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814789995/original  a978-3-11-070644-4  New York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK